Removed the private `_cable_peer`, `_cable_peer_type`, and `_cable_peer_id` cache fields from the `CableTermination` abstract model; cable peers are now resolved on demand via the `CableToCableTermination` join table. Existing public APIs (`get_cable_peer()`, REST `cable_peer`/`cable_peer_type`, GraphQL `cable_peer_*` fields) are unchanged.
`Cable` now exposes typed `ManyToManyField` accessors (`cable.interfaces`, `cable.front_ports`, `cable.power_ports`, etc.) for direct queryset access to each kind of termination on a cable.
Each `CableTermination` instance now exposes a singular reverse `cable_termination` accessor (e.g. `interface.cable_termination`) returning the connected join row, with `select_related("cable_termination")`/`select_related("cable_termination__cable")` supported for batch-fetching.
Removed the `cable` `ForeignKey` from the `CableTermination` abstract model (and from each concrete subclass); replaced with a property that resolves through `cable_termination`. Backward-compatibility query translation (`Interface.objects.filter(cable=...)`, `select_related("cable")`, etc.) is provided with a `DeprecationWarning` pointing at the new `cable_termination__cable[...]` paths. Note: `Q(cable=...)`, `order_by("cable")`, and `values("cable")` are not translated; use the explicit `cable_termination__cable[...]` form.
Removed the private `_path` `ForeignKey` from the `PathEndpoint` abstract model (and from each concrete subclass: `ConsolePort`, `ConsoleServerPort`, `PowerPort`, `PowerOutlet`, `Interface`, `PowerFeed`, `CircuitTermination`). `PathEndpoint` now exposes a `cable_paths` `GenericRelation` that resolves through `CablePath.origin`; the public `path`, `trace()`, `connected_endpoint`, and `get_all_paths()` accessors are unchanged. Query usages of `_path__...` should be rewritten as `cable_paths__...` (note that `cable_paths` is a multi-row reverse relation, so `distinct()` is typically required for `filter()` / `count()` / `exclude()`).
Reworked `InterfaceConnectionsListView` (UI), `InterfaceConnectionViewSet` (REST API), `InterfaceConnectionTable`, `InterfaceConnectionFilterSet`, and the homepage "Interfaces" connection counter to operate over `CablePath` rows rather than `Interface` rows. Each breakout-cable lane now surfaces as its own connection row (previously only the primary lane was shown), and filter parameters (`device_id`, `device`, `location`) now match either endpoint of a connection rather than only the canonical "A" side. The REST API JSON response shape (`interface_a`, `interface_b`, `connected_endpoint_reachable`) is unchanged.
Restored backward-compatibility setters for the `Cable.termination_a`, `Cable.termination_b`, `Cable.termination_a_type`, `Cable.termination_a_id`, `Cable.termination_b_type`, and `Cable.termination_b_id` properties. Assignments are stored on `_initial_*` attributes (matching the `__init__` kwarg path) so that legacy callers (and DRF's default `ModelSerializer.update()`, which calls `setattr(instance, field, value)` for each validated field) no longer raise `AttributeError`.
`CablePath.from_origin()` now bails out cleanly with `is_split=True` when the trace encounters a breakout cable past the origin's directly-connected hop (e.g. an MPO trunk between pass-through ports in a cross-connect cabinet), and also when called on a breakout-cable origin without a lane-specific `far_end_override` (typically because the lane has no far-side termination yet). In both cases the partial path stops cleanly rather than producing an arbitrary destination via the cable's first peer.
Fixed `disconnect_termination()` for breakout cables. The old implementation called `peer.cable_paths.all().delete()` for the cable peer and `termination.cable_paths.all().delete()` for the disconnecting termination — both too coarse-grained for breakout cables, where one side may have multiple paths and only the lane(s) involving the disconnected termination should be affected. The new implementation deletes only the `CableToCableTermination` row and lets `rebuild_paths(cable)` correctly re-derive every path that traversed the cable.
Fixed `rebuild_paths()` for breakout cables: origins are now deduplicated (a single trunk-side PathEndpoint owns multiple CablePaths on a breakout cable; `create_cablepath` builds them all in one call), and when invoked on a `Cable` the function now also enumerates the cable's current PathEndpoint terminations so newly-added join rows are picked up alongside the origins of existing paths through the cable.
Added `Cable.add_termination(termination, cable_end, connector=None, position=None)` for attaching a `CableTermination` to a saved Cable after creation (e.g. for additional breakout lanes that the single A/B `Cable.__init__` kwargs can't express). The method creates the `CableToCableTermination` row and triggers `rebuild_paths` in one call; for bulk additions, the docstring notes that creating the rows directly and calling `rebuild_paths(cable)` once at the end is more efficient than calling `add_termination` N times.
Added `PathEndpoint.get_connected_endpoints()` returning the destinations of all `CablePath` rows originating from the endpoint (one per breakout lane). The "Connection" column on `PathEndpointTable` now uses this accessor instead of `get_cable_peers`, so the rendered value reflects the resolved far-end of the cable path rather than the immediate cable peer.
Generalized the "Edit cable / Disconnect / Delete cable" dropdown on the `Interface` detail view into a shared `dcim/inc/cable_actions.html` include (which renders the existing trace button alongside the actions from `dcim/inc/cable_toggle_buttons.html`). The `ConsolePort`, `ConsoleServerPort`, `PowerPort`, `PowerOutlet`, `FrontPort`, and `RearPort` detail views now expose the same dropdown, including the "Mark connected/planned" cable status toggle previously only available from the row-action dropdowns.
`nautobot.dcim.termination_field_set.detect_termination_type()` and `CableTerminationFieldSet.get_fields()` now raise `ValueError` when given an unrecognized termination object or `term_type` string, rather than silently falling back to `"interface"`. The `None` fallback for blank forms is preserved.
